TI  - Enhancing thermal energy storage: The impact of inclined enclosure geometry and artificial neural network based modeling on phase change material melting performance
T2  - JOURNAL OF ENERGY STORAGE
AB  - This study investigates the heat transfer dynamics and phase change behavior of Lauric acid in different Phase Change Material (PCM) enclosure configurations during the melting process. Four enclosure designs are analyzed: a rectangular enclosure and three enclosures with inclined walls at angles of 30 degrees, 45 degrees, and 60 degrees. A constant temperature of 70 degrees C is applied to the right wall, with temperature propagation and liquid fraction evolution monitored. Artificial intelligence (AI) techniques, specifically artificial neural networks (ANN) trained using the Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm, are utilized to model and predict the liquid fraction for Case 01, demonstrating the robustness and precision of the proposed solutions. Results indicate that the rectangular enclosure (Case 01) has the longest melting time (11,040 s) and the highest heat storage values, with sensible heat at 64.8KJ and total heat storage at 191.5KJ. Inclined enclosures reduce melting times: 30 degrees (Case 02) achieves 9200 s (16.66 % time saving), 45 degrees (Case 03) reduces further to 8440 s (23.55 % time saving), and 60 degrees (Case 04) reaches 8200 s (25.72 % time saving). Increased inclinations enhance convection currents, accelerating heat transfer and melting. However, these reductions in melting time led to decreased heat storage, with Case 04 having the lowest values (62.41KJ sensible heat and 189.11KJ total heat). Economic analysis, based on the costeffectiveness metric (Pc), reveals that Case 03 demonstrates the highest economic performance (Pc = 2.66), balancing optimal melting time with high total energy storage. These findings underscore that modifying PCM enclosure shapes enhances both thermal and economic efficiency, highlighting the importance of integrating AI- based modeling with geometric optimization for superior Thermal Energy Storage (TES) system design.
